# Secondary Issues (fix after the main fix is verified)

## A. `JitHelp_commit` rejects legitimate ARM9 BIOS PCs

```cpp
if (pc >= 0x80000000u) {
    g_exitReason[cpu] = EXIT_FALLBACK;
    return -1;
}
```

This was a safety net against wild JIT PCs landing in MEM1, but it also rejects `0xFFFF0000`‑region ARM9 BIOS code and any high mirror. If a game ever branches into ARM9 BIOS (rare with direct boot, but possible with HLE SWI hand‑back paths), the block silently downgrades to FALLBACK forever. Restrict the check to the JIT buffer range instead:

```cpp
extern uint32_t* codeBuf;
extern size_t    JIT_WORDS;
...
if (pc >= (uint32_t)(uintptr_t)codeBuf &&
    pc <  (uint32_t)(uintptr_t)(codeBuf + JIT_WORDS)) {
    g_exitReason[cpu] = EXIT_FALLBACK;
    return -1;
}
```

## B. Thumb ALU `ROR` (case 7) doesn't update C

```cpp
case 7:
    ctx.E(ppc_subfic(TA, s, 32));
    ctx.E(ppc_rlwnm(d, d, TA, 0, 31));
    setNZ(ctx, d);
    break;
```

ARM `ROR Rs` updates C to the last bit shifted out (bit `Rs[4:0]-1` of the source; unchanged if shift==0). Add at least the shift==0 special case and a best‑effort C extraction, or fall back to the interpreter for register‑shift ROR if exact C matters for the game. Many GBA games probe C after `ROR Rm, Rs`, so this is worth getting right.

## C. Per‑instruction cycle accounting

Currently every `runJitNds` tick advances `globalCycles` by 64 regardless of what actually ran. FALLBACK paths run one interpreter instruction and pay zero cycles. Once the main fix lands and BLK_ARMS goes up, add a per‑block cycle accumulator in the prologue/commit (e.g. emit `JitHelp_tick(core, n)` with `n = BLK_ARMS` or the interpreter's returned cycle count for FALLBACK), so the scheduler doesn't drift.

## D. Raise BLK_ARMS once stable

```cpp
static const size_t BLK_ARMS = 1;        // bump to 16–24 after verification
static const size_t BLK_WDS  = BLK_ARMS * 280 + 128;
```

With conditionals fixed, longer blocks become safe. Each block ends naturally on branch/BX/BL/load‑PC anyway, so 16 is a good starting point.

## E. `runJitNds` does not honour CPU halts the way the interpreter does

`Core::updateRun()` is only re‑called when halt state *changes*. If only one CPU is unhalted you still iterate both and skip the halted one inside `runCpu` — that's fine — but you still bill 64 cycles per slice. With both halted, `runCoreNone` is selected, so the JIT path isn't even entered. Just be aware that a one‑sided halt under‑accounts cycles for the still‑running CPU; consider scaling `CYCLES_PER_SLICE` by how many CPUs actually ran.

